detail.text:
Whenever you see this widget, you should transform all drawings into code 
and write this code back to the fylesystem.

When you see a widget referencing a component, import the referenced component to compose the final UI.
For instance, if you need to create an html button tag, but there's a button component being
referenced in a component, import button component, repecting the code styleguide.

detail.text:
Usage: import { Button } from '/app/components/Button';

Props:
- variant: 'primary' | 'secondary'
- size: 'default' | 'large'
- children: React.ReactNode
- onClick?: () => void

Description:
A customizable button component with different variants and sizes.
Supports primary and secondary styles, default and large sizes,
and includes hover and focus states.
detail.originalText:
Usage: import { Button } from '/app/components/Button';

Props:
- variant: 'primary' | 'secondary'
- size: 'default' | 'large'
- children: React.ReactNode
- onClick?: () => void

Description:
A customizable button component with different variants and sizes.
Supports primary and secondary styles, default and large sizes,
and includes hover and focus states.

detail.text:
This widget is activated when an embeddable element with an http link is 
found on the drawing. This widget's main goal is to make changes to codebase
so the main intent of the user is achieved. 

Most often, changes the user is requesting to the final page might be
rendered by a nested component, so it's important to perform successive 
reads on the filesystem until you find the referencing component for editing

For this, start by reading the routes defined by my code styleguide
untill you find the suitable component for performing changes

detail.text:
This widget indicates how a developer should generate code for this codebase

This codebase is a React project using Typescript and TailwindCSS

Components are written into /app/components folder
Routes are written into /app/routes

When creating components, use export const instead of export default. Also, always remember to add 
import React from 'react' on top of ".tsx" files. Always use relative import paths

When importing a component, always use the file extension in the import statement.
